      <hedline>
        <hl1>Advice to G.O.P.: Veer to the Center</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Michael J Gorman letter, commenting on August 1 article on start of Republican National Convention in Philadelphia, says party must move toward political center or abandon all hope of victory in November</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Republicans Open Convention, Emphasizing Unity'' (front page, Aug. 1):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Republicans Open Convention, Emphasizing Unity'' (front page, Aug. 1):</p>
        <p>In order to have a chance of winning in November, the Republican Party must learn one thing from its convention speakers Colin L. Powell and John McCain, who are strikingly moderate compared with the ''hard right'' of Tom DeLay, Trent Lott, Newt Gingrich and Dick Armey.</p>
        <p>It must move toward the political center or abandon all hope of victory.</p>
        <p>The Republicans simply cannot indulge their ideological excesses and still hope for success in the general election.</p>
        <p>MICHAEL J. GORMAN  Whitestone, Queens, Aug. 1, 2000</p>
      </block>
